                          "gap": 12,
                          "padding": 16,
                          "children": [
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "b6QKt",
                              "fill": "#ffffffff",
                              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                              "width": "fill_container",
                              "content": "Cauchy sequences & completeness",
                              "lineHeight": 1.3,
                              "fontFamily": "PP Mori",
                              "fontSize": 14,
                              "fontWeight": "600"
                            },
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "n8pzgs",
                              "fill": "#ffffff80",
                              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                              "width": "fill_container",
                              "content": "§ 3.4 · Cauchy Sequences",
                              "lineHeight": 1.4,
                              "fontFamily": "PP Mori",
                              "fontSize": 10,
                              "fontWeight": "600",
                              "letterSpacing": 0.6
                            },
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "NCu2F",
                              "fill": "#ffffffe6",
                              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                              "width": "fill_container",
                              "content": "Definition 3.4.1. A sequence {xₙ} in a metric space (M, d) is called a Cauchy sequence if for every ε > 0 there exists N ∈ ℕ such that d(xₙ, xₘ) < ε for all n, m ≥ N.",
                              "lineHeight": 1.5,
                              "fontFamily": "PP Mori",
                              "fontSize": 12,
                              "fontWeight": "normal"
                            },
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "MQOxK",
                              "fill": "#ffffffcc",
                              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                              "width": "fill_container",
                              "content": "Remark. Every convergent sequence is Cauchy; the converse holds iff the space is complete. The rationals ℚ with the standard metric furnish a counterexample.",
                              "lineHeight": 1.5,
                              "fontFamily": "PP Mori",
                              "fontSize": 12,
                              "fontWeight": "normal"
                            },
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "CdHBS",
                              "fill": "#ffffffcc",
                              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                              "width": "fill_container",
                              "content": "Theorem 3.4.2 (Completeness of ℝ). The real line ℝ, equipped with the absolute-value metric, is complete: every Cauchy sequence of real numbers converges to a real limit.",
                              "lineHeight": 1.5,
                              "fontFamily": "PP Mori",
                              "fontSize": 12,
                              "fontWeight": "normal"
                            }
                          ]
                        }
                      ]
